etymology.description: phonetic 五 (wǔ, 'five') + semantic 口 (kǒu, 'mouth') = personal pronoun 'I' using voice
etymology.interpretation: The character 吾 is a phono-semantic compound that combines 五 (wǔ, 'five') to suggest the sound with 口 (kǒu, 'mouth'), which represents speaking or vocalization. This combination emphasizes the personal pronoun 'I,' reflecting verbal self-reference.

examples.chinese: 吾行于天下(吾行於天下)，求知若渴(求知若渴)。
examples.pinyin: wú xíng yú tiān xià, qiú zhī ruò kě
examples.english: I travel the world, seeking knowledge as if I were thirsty.
